06435nam a22008895i 9789048555475DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485554757 a10.1515/97890485554752doi  a(DE-B1597)651440  a(OCoLC)1378570830  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aHM883 7aHIS0540002bisacsh04a303.48404aThe Visual Memory of Protest /ced. by Thomas Smits, Ann Rigney. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aProtest and Social Movements ;v2700tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tThe Visual Memory of Protest: Introduction -- tProducing Memorable Images -- t1 Photojournalism, the World Press Photo Awards , and the Visual Memory of Protest -- t2 The Photographs of Nair Benedicto and the Memory of Protest in Brazil -- t3 Deniz Gezmiş Takes to the Streets: From Photograph to Silhouette -- tReproduction and Remediation -- t4 Photography, Memory, and Women in May '68 -- t5 Scarcity in Visual Memory: Creating a Mural of Sylvia Pankhurst -- t6 Memory, Iconicity, and Virality in Action: Exploring Protest Photos Online -- tMobilizing Visual Memory -- t7 Visual Memory in Grassroots Mobilizations : The Case of the Anti- Corruption Movement of 2011 in India -- t8 Visual Activism in Protests against Disappearances : The Photo-Portraits of the 43 Ayotzinapa Students -- t9 Space and Place in Online Visual Memory : The Tank Man in Hong Kong, 2013-2020 -- tList of Illustrations -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aSocial movements are not only remembered in personal experience, but also through cultural carriers that shape how later movements see themselves and are seen by others. The present collection zooms in on the role of photography in this memory-activism nexus. How do iconographic conventions shape images of protest? Why do some images keep movements in the public eye, while others are quickly forgotten? What role do images play in linking different protests, movements, and generations of activists? Have the affordances of digital media made it easier for activists to use images in their memory politics, or has the digital production and massive online exchange of images made it harder to identify and remember a movement via a single powerful image? Bringing together experts in visual culture, cultural memory, social movements, and digital humanities, this collection presents new empirical, theoretical, and methodological insights into the visual memory of protest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollective memory. 0aProtest movements in mass media. 0aProtest movements. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aConflict and Peace. 4aContemporary Society. 4aCultural Studies. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aactivism, protest, cultural memory, visual representation.1 aChakraborty, Anwesha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDufays, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErbil, Duygu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMattoni, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMemou, Antigoni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerrill, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRigney, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRigney, Ann, eeditor.4edt4http://id